2 <a href="javascript:card_browser(33)">Saruman&#39;s Power</a>    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> <HR><i>*** Update 9/20/02 ***<br>
Add 1 Saelbeth (I&#39;ve tested, he&#39;s good)<br>
Switch the Sleep to another Secret Sentinals (I just like it better)<br>
Switch Bounder for Betrayal of Isenguard  >:)<br>
Add 1 Uruk Warrior<br>
**********************</i><HR><br>
<br>
This Deck speaks for itself, Its a Machine. <br>
Current tournament record - 52-6<br>
So you might ask; "John, why does this deck kick sooo much @ss???"<br>
Well, its a combination of things:<br>
<UL><LI>Abilty to win in multiple ways - This deck gets about 2/3 of its wins from the fellowship, 1/3 with its shadow. Uruk can consistantly slow people down throughout the game, allowing the fellowship to move ahead, but they can also finnish the job when its neccesary (Slopes of Amon Hen is sick!).<br>
<br>
<LI>Flow and Card Drawing - Part of this aspect is the player, You need to know what you need. Dump your uruks for fellowship stuff early, but leave a few lingering around in your hand at the later sites... when they actually matter. Get your fellowship pumped asap. Elrond, Ottar, and Abondoning Reason will help you set this up quickly. Then Durring the later site hold your minions, If your opponent has been moving head-to-head with you, they&#39;ll have the option of moving to site 9, but with a Saruman and 5-7 Uruks in your hand, he&#39;ll just soil himself and stay.<br>
<br>
<LI>Ability to kill minions by the dozen - big Gandalf, huge Aragorn, Archery, Servants, and Great backup gives me more then enough resorces to slaughter Uruk, Nazgul, and Orcs alike.<br>
<br>
<LI>Ownage Prevention - An Ideal game for me is one where only Aragorn and Gandalf skirmish, I have servants exactly when I want them and end up winning all my skirmishes without a scratch on me... but since that never happens, I keep around some good ol&#39; ownage prevention. Filbert, Thrarin, Boromir (Son of Denethor!), and Armor help keep me alive vs. minions I usually can&#39;t beat; Cave Troll, Balrog, Witch King w/ Pale Blade.... or just a nasty orc swarm my archery just isnt enough for.</UL><br>
<br>
<b>STUFF TO KNOW-</b><br>
I bid 4-6, and start Legolas + Sam, or Aragorn if I get out-bid by a non-pony player. My fellowship pisses in the pool alot, but It can take what it dishes out, it has a finely tuned balance of card drawing, archery, aragorn/gandalf pumpers, and R@PE protection. The shadow is just strait beats, saruman and a horde of beefy uruks. I was playing this deck +/- a few cards on day 1 and 2, and it performed pretty well... I still wish I woulda beat Andrew Morris though, I would have played Yako in the Semi-finals and hopefully beat him like I did on day 1. I was using 2 PATHS at DragonCon, but I decided to take &#39;um out, they flow horibly, and just didn&#39;t seem to be there when i really needed &#39;um. I also recently added a 3rd Elrond, cause it kinda sucks to pay 4 for him durring the mid/late game and drawing him early means he draws more.<br>
<br>
<b>BAD@SSES- Everyone who has beaten this deck (In order of Bad@ssness)</b><br>
1. <B>*Andrew Morris*</B> (Andrew is the man. He beat $275 outta me :(<br>
2. <B>*Mike Kessling*</B> (the guy who should have won DragonCon)<br>
3. <B>*Fred Foure and Hayes Hunter*</B> (I only lost to them while testing, but they diserves to be up here. Lossing to them won me a few games at DragonCon.)<br>
4. <B>*Lucas Stephens*</B> <br>
5. Nate Foure<br>
6. Edwin Harris (he came, he saw, he ate my children)<br>
7. Brad Hilton (timed loss, I woulda won)<br>
<br>
(I would list all the people who have lost to this deck, but I don&#39;t have all day :)<br>
